## Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js App Router project.

### Changes Made:

1. **Package Installation**
   - Installed `@vercel/analytics` package version ^1.4.1
   - Updated `package.json` with the new dependency
   - Updated `package-lock.json` with resolved dependencies

2. **Code Changes**
   - Modified `/src/app/layout.tsx`:
     - Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
     - Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after all other providers
     - Followed the official Next.js App Router pattern from Vercel's documentation

### Implementation Details:

The implementation follows the official Vercel Analytics quickstart guide for Next.js App Router projects:
- Fetched the latest documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
- Used the framework-specific setup for Next.js App Router
- Placed the `<Analytics />` component at the end of the body, following best practices
- Preserved all existing code structure and functionality

### Verification:

✅ Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
✅ Linter passed with `npm run lint` (no new errors introduced)
✅ All existing tests and functionality remain intact

### Next Steps:

After deploying this code to Vercel:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard's Analytics section
2. Analytics will start tracking visitor data automatically
3. View analytics data in the Vercel dashboard under the Analytics tab

The analytics component will automatically track page views and user interactions once deployed to Vercel.
